{"id":"1810.01432","submitter":"George Cantwell","authors":"George T. Cantwell and M. E. J. Newman","title":"Mixing patterns and individual differences in networks","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 99, 042306 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.99.042306","report-no":"Phys. Rev. E 99, 042306 (2019)","categories":"cs.SI physics.soc-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study mixing patterns in networks, meaning the propensity for nodes of\ndifferent kinds to connect to one another. The phenomenon of assortative\nmixing, whereby nodes prefer to connect to others that are similar to\nthemselves, has been widely studied, but here we go further and examine how and\nto what extent nodes that are otherwise similar can have different preferences.\nMany individuals in a friendship network, for instance, may prefer friends who\nare roughly the same age as themselves, but some may display a preference for\nolder or younger friends. We introduce a network model that captures this\nbehavior and a method for fitting it to empirical network data. We propose\nmetrics to characterize the mean and variation of mixing patterns and show how\nto infer their values from the fitted model, either using maximum-likelihood\nestimates of model parameters or in a Bayesian framework that does not require\nfixing any parameters.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 2 Oct 2018 18:01:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 17 Apr 2019 20:35:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-24"}
